SIMPLE: skill
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Skill
<hw>Skill</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Icel. <ets>skil</ets> a
distinction, discernment; akin to <ets>skilja</ets> to separate, divide,
distinguish, Sw. <ets>skilja</ets>,. <ets>skille</ets> to separate,
<ets>skiel</ets> reason, right, justice, Sw. <ets>sk⟦aum⟧l</ets> reason,
Lith. <ets>skelli</ets> to cleave. Cf. <er>Shell</er>, <er>Shoal</er>, a
multitude.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Discrimination; judgment; propriety;
reason; cause.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>Shak.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧As it was
<xex>skill</xex> and right.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Chaucer.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For great <qex>skill</qex> is, he prove that he wrought.</q> [For
with good reason he should test what he created.]
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Knowledge; understanding.</def>
<mark>[Obsoles.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That by his fellowship he color might⟦br⟧
Both his estate and love from <qex>skill</qex> of any wight.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nor want we <qex>skill</qex> or art.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The familiar knowledge of any art or science, united
with readiness and dexterity in execution or performance, or in the
application of the art or science to practical purposes; power to
discern and execute; ability to perceive and perform; expertness;
aptitude; <as>as, the <ex>skill</ex> of a mathematician, physician,
surgeon, mechanic, etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Phocion, . . . by his great wisdom and <qex>skill</qex> at
negotiations, diverted Alexander from the conquest of Athens.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Where patience her sweet <qex>skill</qex> imparts.</q>
<rj><qau>Keble.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Display of art; exercise of ability; contrivance;
address.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Richard . . . by a thousand princely <qex>skills</qex>, gathering
so much corn as if he meant not to return.</q>
<rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Any particular art.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Learned in one <qex>skill</qex>, and in another kind of learning
unskillful.</q> <rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Dexterity; adroitness; expertness; art; aptitude;
ability.</syn> -- <usage><er>Skill</er>, <er>Dexterity</er>,
<er>Adroitness</er>. <xex>Skill</xex> is more intelligent, denoting
familiar knowledge united to readiness of performance.
<xex>Dexterity</xex>, when applied to the body, is more mechanical, and
refers to habitual ease of execution. <xex>Adroitness</xex> involves the
same image with <xex>dexterity</xex>, and differs from it as implaying a
general facility of movement (especially in avoidance of danger or in
escaping from a difficalty). The same distinctions apply to the
figurative sense of the words. A man is <xex>skillful</xex> in any
employment when he understands both its theory and its practice. He is
<xex>dexterous</xex> when he maneuvers with great lightness. He is
<xex>adroit</xex> in the use od quick, sudden, and well-directed
movements of the body or the mind, so as to effect the object he has in
view.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Skill</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Skill
<hw>Skill</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To know; to
understand.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>skill</qex> the arts of expressing our mind.</q>
<rj><qau>Barrow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Skill</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Skill
<hw>Skill</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To be knowing; to have
understanding; to be dexterous in performance.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I can not <qex>skill</qex> of these thy ways.</q>
<rj><qau>Herbert.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make a difference; to signify; to matter; -- used
impersonally.</def> <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What <qex>skills</qex> it, if a bag of stones or gold⟦br⟧
About thy neck do drown thee?</q> <rj><qau>Herbert.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It <qex>skills</qex> not talking of it.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Skilled</ent>⟦br⟧
